Topic
Purpose
JWT Authentication
Verifies user identity and issues a signed token after login.
Token Generation
Creates a JWT containing user identity and claims after successful authentication.
Token Validation
Verifies the token's signature, expiration, and claims on every request.
RBAC
Restricts access to URLs or resources based on user roles or authorities.
Method-Level Security
Protects individual service or controller methods using annotations such as @PreAuthorize.
CORS
Allows trusted web applications hosted on different origins to call your REST APIs.
CSRF
Protects cookie-based applications from forged requests; commonly disabled for stateless JWT APIs.
Secure REST APIs
Combine HTTPS, strong password hashing, short-lived JWTs, refresh tokens, input validation, exception handling, rate limiting, and security headers to build production-ready APIs.




JWT contains three parts
xxxxx.yyyyy.zzzzz
Example
eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIs...
.
eyJzdWIiOiJqYXki...
.
sdfjksdf98sd7f9s...
Part 1: Header
Part 2: Payload
Part 3: Signature






